05348nam a22007815i 9780824873875DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20052005hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248738757 a10.1515/97808248738752doi  a(DE-B1597)484134  a(OCoLC)1024033074  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aHIS0080002bisacsh0483pa950qDE-10100aCrossed Histories :bManchuria in the Age of Empire /ced. by Mariko Asano Tamanoi. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (224 p.) :billus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsian Interactions and Comparisons ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editor’s Preface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Manchuria in Mind: Press, Propaganda, and Northeast China in the Age of Empire, 1930–1937 -- t2. City Planning without Cities: Order and Chaos in Utopian Manchukuo -- t3. Princess, Traitor, Soldier, Spy: Aisin Gioro Xianyu and the Dilemma of Manchu Identity -- t4. Goodwill Hunting: Rediscovering and Remembering Manchukuo in Japanese ‘‘Goodwill Films’’ -- t5. Colonized Colonizers: The Poles in Manchuria -- t6. Those Who Imitated the Colonizers: The Legacy of the Disciplining State from Manchukuo to South Korea -- t7. Pan-Asianism in the Diary of Morisaki Minato (1924– 1945), and the Suicide of Mishima Yukio (1925–1970) -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCrossed Histories represents a collaborative and interdisciplinary approach to "Manchuria" under Japan’s influence from the turn of the twentieth century to 1945. The contributors, who represent the fields of history, literature, film studies, sociology, and anthropology, unpack the complexity of Manchuria as an effect of the geopolitical imaginaries of various individuals and groups shaped by imperialism, colonialism, Pan-Asianism, and the present globalization. Manchuria is thus examined in the imaginations of a Chinese journalist and his Shanghai readers in the 1930s; prewar Japanese city planners and architects; a Manchu princess later executed by the Chinese nationalist government; various audiences of Japanese "goodwill films" of the 1930s and 1940s; the seven thousand Poles who immigrated to northern Manchuria in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries; the state makers of Manchukuo (which included both Japanese and Chinese leaders) and North and South Korea during the Cold War era; and a student of Manchuria Nation- Building University in the mid-1940s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aAsano Tamanoi, Mariko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsanoTamanoi, Mariko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaskett, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHan, Suk-Jung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLahusen, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitter, Rana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShao, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTamanoi, Mariko Asano, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTucker, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082487387540uhttps://